v class=\"post-info__item-label\">TOOLS<\/div><div class=\"post-info__item-value\">ADOBE AFTER EFFECTS, TOUCH DESIGNER<\/div><\/div><\/div><\/header><div class=\"t-box-b post-detail__body\"><nav class=\"post-detail__tabs\"><div class=\"post-detail__tab-dot is--active\"><\/div><ul class=\"post-detail__tab-list\"><div class=\"post-detail__tab is--active\">OVERVIEW<\/div><div class=\"post-detail__tab false\">CHALLENGE<\/div><div class=\"post-detail__tab false\">REFLECTION<\/div><\/ul><\/nav><div class=\"post-detail__tab-body\"><ul class=\"post-detail__tab-body-list\"><div class=\"post-detail__tab-body-item is--active\">Created a looping motion poster for Shinichi Maruyama, mainly inspired by the Light Sculpture series.<br><br>To further challenge myself, I used Touch Designer for the first time to explore more with particles and integrating type in this piece.\u00a0<\/div><div class=\"post-detail__tab-body-item false\">As my first time with TouchDesigner, I needed to balance control with aesthetic clarity. How do I recreate the ambiance, the simple yet complex physical work but execute it well digitally?<\/div><div class=\"post-detail__tab-body-item false\">There\u2019s beauty in the unexpected: real\u2011time tools teach you to design with the system, not against it.\u00a0<br>Even if in a short amount of time, would&#8217;ve been best to nail down concept\/ choose the artwork first, then experiment from there.<\/div><\/ul><\/div><div class=\"post-detail__media-container\"><picture class=\"post-detail__media-image\"><source media=\"(max-width:600px)\" srcset=\"https:\/\/jasminegunarto.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2026\/01\/rainbowcircles-1.webp\"\/><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/jasminegunarto.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2026\/01\/rainbowcircles-1.webp\"\/><\/picture><picture class=\"post-detail__media-image\"><source media=\"(max-width:600px)\" srcset=\"https:\/\/jasminegunarto.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2026\/01\/movingposter3.webp\"\/><img decoding=\"async\" src=